color support/displai
 mac: 30.24 mhz pixel clock standard.  all present mac support the us of 
32-bit color through 32-bit color quickdraw in rom.  32-bit color quickdraw 
allow an almost transpar capabl to displai and edit x-bit imag in y-
bit color and retain all the color of y-bit color [where x and y 
independ ar 1, 2, 4, 8, 16, or 32] regardless of monitor resolut {63 
dpi [12" color] to 94 dpi [palettebook]} or monitor type {includ 
autosynchron vga, mcga and svga monitor with rang includ 66.7 hz 
vertic and 35 khz horizont and onli a hardwar video adaptor (macus 
aug 1992: 158-176).  older machin that support color {se/30, ii, iix, and 
iicx} had onli 8-bit color in rom and need a softwar patch to us 32-bit 
color (macus special 1993:28-29).  
to keep cost down and speed up most mac have onli 8 or 16 bit displai 
capabl built-in, but most of those can be expand to displai 24-bit 
color.    present quickdraw is optim for 72 dpi displai; quickdraw qx 
will chang thi.
in addit, quickdraw allow, in mac with a nubu slot, more then on 
monitor to be us in ani combin, from two monitor show the same 
thing to multipl monitor act as on larg larg monitor with ani degre 
of overlap of the pictur.
vram: video ram.  standard for present non-powerbook mac's handl of 
 built-in video {from a 32-bit color palett}. vram provid run a 8-bit
 color 640x480 displai; expand to 16-bit color or a 8-bit 832x624 displai. 
sound output:  standard in all mac sinc the 128k.  stereo sound becam 
 standard with the se/30.

ibm:  even though pc have rom bio definit of how the oper system 
interact with the video hardwar (nan zou), the us of driver bypass 
bio, video harewar inconsit {see super vga below} and nonstanderz
of clone bio have left resolut of video displai hardwar, os and program 
interact up to the os and video hardwar in question (faisal nameer 
jawdat). in addit, ibm and clone maker never bother to provid a 
standard hardwar mechan for softwar to determin what displai mode is 
actual present (matt heali) nor a standard screen-draw toolbox {like 
mac's qd}. as a result the os must be veri well written to detect some mode, 
especi with some third parti card or to us them consitantli {at present 
thing ar so depend on the interact of the program, os, print driver 
and monitor card that edit 32-bit pictur regardless of color mode, os, 
and monitor type/card combin as on can do on the mac is imposs with 
an ibm.  for exampl, on cannot edit a 32-bit color pictur done on a os/2 
486 with a svga monitor on a 386 with vga {18-bit color palett} and do 5.0 
and still have all the color on start out with}.
later ibm machin will have integr graphic acceler, faster 
processor, and modular upgrad and mai have built-in sound card, cd 
rom, and ethernet (pc week 12/14/92).  
mda: monocrom displai adapt
 origin charact-map video mode, no graphic, 80x25 text.
cga: color graphic arrai
 320x200 4 color or 640x200 b/w, 16 color palett, bad for the ey.
ega:  enhanc graphic arrai
 640x350 16 color from 64 color palett [and some lower re]; some version 
 could run at 256 color, bearabl on the ey.
vga:  video graphic arrai*
 320x200 at 256 color, 640x480 at 16 color, and some other, these two ar 
 the most commonli us.  all mode have a 256k clut, from a 
 18 to 24-bit {ibm} or a 32-bit {mac} color palett.  25.175 mhz pixel clock
 (mel martinez).  monitor us analog input, incompat with ttl signal
 from ega/cga etc. 
mcga:  multi-color graphic arrai*
 subset of vga that provid all the featur of mda & cga, but lack some ega 
 and vga mode, like vga 640x480x16 (dictionari of comput term-dct).  
 common on the initi ps/1 implement from ibm and some ps/2 model.
svga:  super vga*
 thi is not a standard in the wai the other were, but instead wa a 'catch 
 all' categori for a group of video card.  as such, with each manufactur 
 us their own implement scheme, svga wa chao with peopl debat
 as to what is svga and what is not.  in an effort to make svga more of a 
 standard vesa wa establish and is us in the newer unit, but thing
 ar still a mess.  video is either 512k [~1990] or 1m [todai], resolut
 of 800x600 and 1024x768 at 16 and 256 color ar common, newer on [sinc 
 1990] have the sierra hicolor ramdac, give 15-bit 32,768 color at 800x600, 
 some of the veri newer on [~6/92] can do 24 bit per pixel [usual 
 at 640x480].  speedwis, too much variat, some veri slow [western digit 
 paradis base, for exampl], some veri fast [s3 86c911 base, for exampl], 
 some ar so-so [like tseng et4000, a veri popular chipset].  some limit 
 factor overcom by 40mhz vl bu & 386's linear address map were: 
 8.33 mhz isa bu, at architectur where the cpu look at the card through a 
 64k "window", etc.
other non-svga standard: 
8514/a:
 ibm's own standard, interlac graphic acceler with graphic function 
 like linedraw, polygon fill, etc. in hardwar. some clone implement 
 from ati ar the fastest video avail todai, though some clone model do 
 not have interlac. 
tm34010/34020: high end graphic co-processor, usual >$1000, some
 do 24-bit, speed up vector-orient graphic like cad.
xga:  extend graphic arrai
 newer and faster than 8514/a, onli avail for mca bu-base ps/2s, clone 
 ar come out soon.  emul vga, ega, and cga (dct).  max resolut at 
 1024x768x8b, same as 8514/a, also some 16 bpp mode.
xga-2
 acceler graphic function up to 20 time faster than standard vga in
 window and os/2, includ line draw, bit and pixel-block transfer, area
 fill, mask and x/y address. ha an intellig wai to detect and co-
 exist with other xga-2 card, so multipl desktop like on the mac mai not be 
 far awai.  sinc thi is an architectur, it resolut and color depth 
 isn't fix {ibm implement onli 16-bit [65,536] color, while other 
 compani can have 24-bit color through ibm technic licens}. refresh 
 rate up to 75 hz, ensur flicker free, rock solid imag to reduc visual 
 discomfort, and is vga compat. up to 1280x1024 on os/2.
